<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Office of the Children’s Commissioner (LAI 0023)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Office of the Children’s Commissioner welcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Joint Committee on Human Rights’ inquiry into the effect on access to justice of the changes to the legal aid regime proposed by the government in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and now revised in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Legal Aid: Next steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  We have serious concerns regarding the effect of these proposals on access to justice for children and young people and their rights as protected by the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC) and other instruments.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Furth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er, the proposals are likely to have an especially serious impact on some ‘groups of children who do not have other adequate means by which they can make their views known’ – to whom the Children’s Commissioner is required by s2 Children Act 2004 to have p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">articular regard: children in custody; migrant children; and victims of abuse and neglect.  The Committee will be aware of OCC’s response to the first </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consultation: we here offer additional evidence to be read with that document in o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rder to take account of the government’s revised proposals in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Next Steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> document.   OCC is also proposing to undertake a Child Rights Impact Assessment of legal aid changes since April 2013, to be published in summer 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Access to justice under the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> UN Convention on the Rights of the Child</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Access to justice for children is crucial for the protection and realisation of the full range of children’s rights and is specifically guaranteed by Article 12(2) of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘…the child shall in particular be provided the opportunity to be heard in any judicial or administrative proceedings affecting the child, either directly, or through a representative or an appropriate body, in a manner consistent with the procedural rul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">es of national law’. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This applies, amongst other judicial and administrative proceedings, to those dealing with breaches of children’s rights, as the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child (CRC) emphasised in its General Comment no 5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">General measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">of implementation for the Convention on the Rights of the Child</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children’s special and dependent status creates real difficulties for them in pursuing remedies for breaches of their rights.  So States need to give particular attention to ensuring that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">there are effective, child-sensitive procedures available to children and their representatives.  These should include the provision of child-friendly information, advice, advocacy, including support for self-advocacy, and access to independent complaints </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">procedures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">and to the courts with necessary legal and other assistance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The obligation under Article 12 includes children ‘capable of forming views’ (Article 12(1)) and therefore includes younger children as well as older </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">children and young people.  Like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other UNCRC rights it is subject to the non-discrimination guarantee under Article 2 UNCRC in relation to the child’s, or his or her parent or legal guardian’s, ‘race, colour, sex, language, religion, political or other opinion, national, ethnic or social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">origin, property, disability, birth or other status’.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In recommendations following its Day of General Discussion on ‘The right of the child to be heard’ the CRC reminded States Parties that ‘the right of the child to be heard in judicial and administrat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ive proceedings applies to all relevant settings without limitation, including children separated from their parents, custody and adoption cases, children in conflict with the law, children victims of physical violence, sexual abuse and other crimes, asylu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m-seeking and refugee children and children who have been the victims of armed conflict and in emergencies.’ It requested that ‘States Parties establish specialised legal aid support systems in order to provide children involved in administrative and judic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ial proceedings with qualified support and assistance.’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CRC has also emphasised that the obligation to implement Article 12 UNCRC is not dependent on resources. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prison law</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are concerned by the remarks of the Secretary of State in the foreword to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that characterise legal aid in prison law cases as being used ‘to seek an easier life in another prison’.  As members of the UK’s National Preve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntive Mechanism, designated under the Optional Protocol to the UN Convention Against Torture, we visit a range of detention settings for children including youth justice custody: Young Offenders Institutions, Secure Training Centres and Secure Children’s H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omes.  Children in custody are doubly if not triply vulnerable: by virtue of their age and capacity; their position in state detention (often far away from their home and with infrequent or absent family visits); and their other characteristics (vulnerabil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ities such as learning disability and mental illness; prior experience of abuse and neglect; complex care history involving multiple placements; being looked after children often far from their home local authority and with varying levels of contact with t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat authority).  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We note the comments of the Ministry of Justice at paragraph 2.6 of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regarding the role of advocacy services, complaints procedures and the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman/statutory monitor/local authori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ties.  However, complaints mechanisms cannot provide a substitute for the independent judicial scrutiny and binding legal remedies available in court proceedings and we believe that, alone, they cannot effectively protect important rights of children in cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stody, including the rights to freedom from maltreatment and inhuman and degrading treatment or punishment (under Articles 19 and 37 UNCRC and Article 3 European Convention on Human Rights).  While we have seen examples of good practice by dedicated profes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sionals in secure facilities, we have also seen examples of children kept in segregation for long periods with inadequate educational provision; cells that are unfit for habitation; and high levels of restraint including the use of pain-inducing ‘distracti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on’ techniques.  There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already substantial barriers to these children accessing specialist prison law advice: for example, an OCC/User Voice report on children’s views of restraint found an acceptance of restraint amongst boys in custody; the Serious C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ase Review into the self-inflicted death of Alex Kelly in HM YOI Cookham Wood in January 2012 detailed his general distrust of adults following severe sexual abuse in childhood and a complex care history.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; orphans:0; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that the removal of legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in these circumstances will lead to the loss of a remedy in serious cases where children’s treatment in custody is unlawful; the loss of important precedents to guide the future actions of detaining facilities and authorities such as the Youth Justice Boa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rd, in circumstances where the relationship of domestic (often secondary) legislation with children’s rights can be unclear; and the risk that standards will decline as detaining authorities become immune from judicial challenge. A further effect is that m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">others facing separation from their babies due to a decision not to place them in a mother and baby unit will be unable effectively to challenge these decisions;</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this engages the fundamental right of the child not to be separated from his or her parent unless that is in his or her best interests (Article 9 UNCRC).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are pleased that the government has exempted some areas of law from the residence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> test as detailed at paragraph 125 of the Ministry of Justice response to the first </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consultation.  However, in those areas of law that remain subject to the test under the revised proposals important children’s rights will be engaged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  They include, amongst other areas: special educational needs cases engaging the right to education and prohibitions on discrimination against disabled children;</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> community care cases concerning a number of fundamental rights of children in care, in need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and care leavers; cases concerning the need for asylum support of migrant children; judicial review cases not concerning detention;</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and tort and damages claims relating to a significant breach of children’s rights under the European Convention on Human R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ights.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The test will severely compromise the access to justice not only of children not lawfully resident for 12 months (or babies not lawfully present at the time of seeking legal assistance) but also of other children who cannot produce the relevant d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocumentary evidence to show lawful residence.  These children – and in particular those who are unaccompanied, estranged from parents/carers or looked after by the local authority – will have no meaningful access to justice in these cases to secure their r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ights.  It should be emphasised that in some cases even the writing of a solicitor’s letter setting out the relevant law can be sufficient to secure rights that have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overlooked by public authorities (including by ensuring that their best interests are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a primary consideration in relevant decision-making as required by Article 3 UNCRC) – but this assistance will no longer be available to these children.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Judicial review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The changes proposed to legal aid for judicial review cases in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">gal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consultations should be looked at in conjunction with the changes to the availability of and procedure for applications for judicial review proposed in the consultation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: proposals for future reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  In relation to the matters that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are the subject of the Committee’s inquiry – the removal of payment for cases that end before a successful application for permission to proceed, and for cases that are assessed as having ‘borderline’ prospects of success, we are concerned that the combine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d effect of these proposals is seriously to limit the availability of judicial review of executive action and public law remedies for children.  A compromise is proposed in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Next Steps</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – to allow payment in ‘meritorious’ claims that settle before permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but we remain concerned that providers will be unwilling to take on the risk of these cases and will simply withdraw from offering services in relevant areas of the law except to privately paying clients.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In relation to ‘borderline’ cases, these will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">include many important test cases and those establishing important precedents in relation to the protection of children’s rights.  Together we are concerned that these changes will severely limit the availability of judicial review and public law remedies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to children and their parents/carers who cannot afford to pay privately.  The government’s contention that legal aid should not be available where a privately paying client would not risk litigation ignores the overwhelming importance of many of these case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s to the applicant and the children’s rights concerned, including the rights to family life and not to be separated from parents except where it is in the child’s best interests.  The changes would also compound the impact on children in custody of the pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">son law changes discussed above.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">eptember 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Children’s Commissioner’s remit includes all children under 18 in England and young adults aged 18-20 who are care leavers or have a learning disability. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">She also has a duty to speak on behalf of all children in the UK on non-devolved issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s which include immigration, for the whole of the UK, and youth justice, for England and Wales. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> At para 24, emphasis added.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> CRC, Report on the forty-third session, September 2006, Day of General Discussion, Recommendations, paras. 34 to 36 and 38.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ower Hamlets Safeguarding Children Board, August 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Serious Case Review Executive Summary: Services provided for Child F June 2004 – January 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> See Family Law Bar Association, Transforming Legal Aid consultation response.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> See Office of the Childr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">en’s Commissioner (2012), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">They never give up on you</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,  p97ff; and Office of the Children’s Commissioner (2013), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Always Someone Else’s Problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, pp33 and 39 re schools’ awareness of and application of the legal requirements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The recent Administrative Court decision of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Yiyu Chen and others) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">CO/1119/2013, concerning the circumstances in which force may be used against children being removed from the United Kingdom, and in which th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e Children’s Commissioner intervened, is  just one example of an important children’s rights case that would, we believe, have failed the residence test as currently proposed. </span></p></body></html>